quran[30]{c,v,t,f}:
78,1,"About what are they asking one another?"
78,2,"Is it about the awesome tiding"
78,3,"that they are in utter disagreement? {1}",footnotes:1:The great news: the news of the Resurrection and Hereafter
78,4,"No indeed; {1} soon will they come to know; {2}",footnotes:1:That is
78,5,"again, no indeed; soon will they come to know."
78,6,"Have We not spread the earth like a bed, {1}",footnotes:1:Enough light has been thrown at several places in the meaning of the Quran on the supreme wisdom and power of Allah that underlies His making the earth a carpet
78,7,"and fixed the mountains like pegs, {1}",footnotes:1:For the wisdom of creating mountains on the earth
78,8,"and created you in pairs (as men and women), {1}",footnotes:1:For explanation of the supreme wisdom that underlies the creation of men and women into pairs
78,9,"and made your sleep a means of repose, {1}",footnotes:1:The explanation of the wisdom for which Allah Almighty has placed a desire for sleep in man’s nature in order to make him fit for work in the world
78,10,"and made the night a covering,"
78,11,"and made the day to seek livelihood, {1}",footnotes:1:That is
78,12,"and built above you seven strong firmaments, {1}",footnotes:1:Strong
78,13,"and placed therein a hot, shining lamp, {1}",footnotes:1:A bright
78,14,"and sent down abundant water from the clouds"
78,15,"so that We may thereby bring forth grain and vegetation,"
78,16,"and gardens dense with foliage? {1}",footnotes:1:For the details of the wonderful manifestations of Allah Almighty’s power and wisdom in making arrangements for the rain and the growth of vegetation thereby
78,17,"Surely the Day of Judgement has an appointed time;"
78,18,"the Day when the Trumpet shall be blown, and you will come forth in multitudes; {1}",footnotes:1:This implies the final sounding of the Trumpet at which all dead men will rise back to life forthwith. You implies not only those who were the addressees at that time but all those humans who will have been born from the beginning of creation till Resurrection. (For explanation
78,19,"and when the sky shall be opened up and will become all doors;"
78,20,"and the mountains will be set in motion and become a mirage. {1}",footnotes:1:One should bear in mind the fact that here also
78,21,"Surely the Hell is an ambush, {1}",footnotes:1:An ambush: a place contrived to entrap game by surprise. Hell has been described as an ambush
78,22,"a resort for the rebellious;"
78,23,"therein they shall abide for ages, {1}",footnotes:1:The word ahqab as used in the original means successive periods of long time appearing continuously one after the other. From this word some people have tried to argue that there will be eternity in the life of Paradise but no eternity in the life of Hell. For however long these ages may be
78,24,"they shall taste in it no coolness, nor any pleasant drink"
78,25,"save boiling water and wash of the wounds; {1}",footnotes:1:The word ghassaq as used in the original applies to pus
78,26,"a befitting recompense for their deeds."
78,27,"For indeed they did not look forward to any reckoning,"
78,28,"and roundly denied Our Signs as false. {1}",footnotes:1:This is the reason for which they will deserve this dreadful penalty of Hell. Firstly
78,29,"And everything have We recorded in a Book. {1}",footnotes:1:That is
78,30,"So taste (the fruit of your deeds). We shall only increase your torment."
